  <subsection>
    <title>Direction of travel</title>
    <p>
      T is the direction of travel. Should make sense from our discussion of the velocity vector that <m>/vv(t)=\vr'(t)</m> is in the direction of travel. Since speed is not 1 we define the direction of travel as follows.
      <definition xml:id="def-">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The unit tangent vector to a curve is denoted by <m>\vec{T}(t)</m> is computed by 
            <me> \vec{T}(t)=\frac{\vv(t)}{\Vert{\vv(t)}\Vert}</me>
            The unit tangent vector measures the direction of travel along a parameterized curve.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      The unit tangent exists as long as the velocity exists and is not the zero vector. This should make sense because if there is not motion or there is jump/discontinuity in the derivative, the direction of travel at that instant does not make sense. 
    </p>

    <p>
      The definition of T has allowed us to separate the velocity into its magnitude (speed) and direction (unit tangent). Remember that T changes along the curve and is calculated as a function of the parameter. 
      
    </p>
    <example>
      <p>
        Example that shows how to calculuate T for a helix. Should make sense of all of these calculations along the way including looking at t=pi/2 and t=5pi/4. Show that you can use the velocity and speed at a single value to calculate for just one t value.
      </p>
    </example>
    <activity>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find v, speed, and T for a line given by 3t-1,2-2t,5+t
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find v, speed, and T for the curve given by t,t^2,t^3
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find T at the point P if the tangent line to the curve through P is given by 2-7t, 3t+1,-4t-1
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Recalling our analogy of our parameterization describing how we are driving along a racetrack, T measures the direction that that car is heading in at any given moment. Look at t=2 on ounr track, we see that T(2)=  Show a plot with all of this.
      What direction is the car turning at t=2? you can see by the plot that the car will be be turning right/left, but that is a relative direction to the car. So how can we measure the direction that the car is turning at this instant, in terms of the larger coordinate system?
      
    </p>
<p>
  Let's look at <m>\vec{T}'=\frac{d\vec{T}}{dt}</m>, which will measure how quickly <m>\vec{T}</m> is changing in terms of the parameter. Remember that vectors have magnitude and direction, so the derivative of a vector valued function of 1 variable can measure the change in the magnitude and a change in the direction. Since T will always have length 1 (when T exists), all of the change in T will correspond to a change in direction. So the direction of <m>\vec{T}'=\frac{d\vec{T}}{dt}</m> will be exactly what we are looking for; namely, <m>\vec{T}'=\frac{d\vec{T}}{dt}</m> will be in the direction of turning. We don't care (for now) about how fast the car is turning, just what direciton that turning is in. So we define N as the unit vector in the direction of <m>\vec{T}'=\frac{d\vec{T}}{dt}</m>.
</p>
<definition xml:id="def-N">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The unit normal vector to a curve is denoted by <m>\vec{N}(t)</m> is computed by 
            <me> \vec{N}(t)=\frac{\vec{T}'(t)}{\Vert{\vec{T}'(t)}}</me>
            The unit norml vector measures the direction of turning along a parameterized curve.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<p>
  When does N exist/not exist?
</p>
<example>
  <p>
    calculate N for the helix example. Make sense of these results at a few points. Note how clean the calculations come out here.
  </p>
</example>
