</activity>
<p>
  Remember that to find N, we will need to find the second and third components of T', then divide T' by its magnitude (which will be A LOT)
</p>
<p>
  We have talked about how T measures the direction of travel along a parameterized curve and N measures the direction of turning. Can N have any part parallel to T? No. N is parallel to T' and since T does not change length, the derivative of T cannot be parallel to T. All of the change of T has to be a change in direction. Thus T is orthogonal to N
</p>
  </subsection>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-B">
  <title>The Binormal Vector</title>
  <definition xml:id="def-B">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The Binormal vector, <m>\vec{B}</m>, for a parameterized curve is defined as <me> \vec{B}=\vec{T} \times \vec{N}</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    This definition of B creates a three dimensional right handed coordinate system that is relative to the motion along the curve. B will be a unit vector because <m>\Vert \vT \times \vN \Vert = \Vert \vT\Vert \Vert \vN \Vert \sin(theta)</m> where theta is the angle between <m>\vT</m> and <m>\vN</m>. Since <m>\vT</m> and <m>vN</m> are normal vectors and orthogonal to each other, then <m>\Vert \vT\Vert \Vert \vN \Vert \sin(theta)= 1</m>. B will give the axis of rotation for the motion along the curve. Note that this measure of rotation follows our right handed measure of rotation. If you put the fingers of your right hand in the direction of travel (<m>\vT</m>) and curl your fingers in the direction of turning (<m>\vN</m>), then your thumb will correspond to the axis of rotation based on how you are moving along the curve.
  </p>
  <p>
    This TNB frame is sometimes called the Frenet frame and is very useful in environments like aviation and space travel because so much of the relevent information needs be in terms of relative measurements to the craft and it's motion.
  </p>
